# **Database Schema Architecture (SQLite)**

This document details the SQLite database schema (sql/schema\_v1.sql) established in Epic 1, which serves as the foundational data model for The Narrative Forge application.

The structure adheres to a fully relational model, prioritizing data integrity and efficient querying across different content types (Chapters, Lore, Characters, and Versioning).

![Image of database schema diagram][image1]

Shutterstock

## **Core Tables (The Content)**

| Table Name | Purpose | Key Columns | Relationships |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **Chapters** | The primary unit of writing. Stores rich text content and chronological data. | ID (PK), Title, Text\_Content, Sort\_Order, Start\_Date, End\_Date, Precursor\_Chapter\_ID (Self-Referencing FK) | Linked to Tags (via Chapter\_Tags) and Version\_History. |
| **Lore\_Entries** | The world-building wiki and knowledge base. | ID (PK), Title (UNIQUE), Content, Category | Linked to Tags (via Lore\_Tags). |
| **Characters** | Named entities in the narrative. | ID (PK), Name (UNIQUE), Description, Status | Linked to Relationships. |

## **Auxiliary Tables (The Links)**

| Table Name | Purpose | Foreign Key Constraints |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **Tags** | Provides flexible metadata. Has a UNIQUE constraint on the Name. | N/A |
| **Chapter\_Tags** | Many-to-Many link between Chapters and Tags. | Chapter\_ID $\\rightarrow$ Chapters(ID) (ON DELETE CASCADE) |
| **Lore\_Tags** | Many-to-Many link between Lore\_Entries and Tags. | Lore\_ID $\\rightarrow$ Lore\_Entries(ID) (ON DELETE CASCADE) |

## **Utility Tables (The Integrity)**

| Table Name | Purpose | Foreign Key Constraints | Constraints/Notes |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| **Relationships** | Tracks defined connections between two characters. | Character\_A\_ID and Character\_B\_ID $\\rightarrow$ Characters(ID) | Uses a CHECK constraint to ensure Character\_A\_ID is not equal to Character\_B\_ID. |
| **Version\_History** | Stores metadata pointing to archived snapshots of chapter drafts. | Chapter\_ID $\\rightarrow$ Chapters(ID) (ON DELETE CASCADE) | File\_Hash is UNIQUE to prevent saving the exact same content twice. |

## **Key Foreign Key Enforcement**

* **Causality:** The Chapters table uses a self-referencing foreign key (Precursor\_Chapter\_ID) to link a chapter to the one immediately preceding it, enforcing a logical narrative flow for the C++ Chronology Checker (Epic 4).  
* **Data Integrity:** All join tables and utility tables use ON DELETE CASCADE. This ensures that deleting a parent record (e.g., a Chapter) automatically removes all associated metadata (tags, version history), preventing orphaned data.  
* **Performance:** Indexes have been created on all Foreign Key columns to optimize join operations and improve the speed of data lookups.
